dataIdInfo.idAbs: This vector line file represents road, railroad, and municipal boundary centerlines within Monroe County, New York. These centerlines combine for a total of 4,625 centerline miles. According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the County has a total area of 1,366 square miles, of which 659 square miles is land and 706 square miles (51.72%) is water. This layer has been continously updated by the Monroe County Department of Environmental Services since it received the file in 2001 from the Genesee/Finger Lakes Regional Planning Council. It is currently maintained with information provided by the 9-1-1 Emergency Communications Department (ECD), tax parcel data obtained from Monroe County Real Property Services, as well as current aerial photography, street abandonment and dedication reports, and input from municipalities. This layer is the single authoritative source of centerline information in Monroe County.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The purpose of this layer is to represent the geography and attributes of road, railroad, and municipal boundary centerlines within Monroe County, New York. It is a critical basemap layer and is used for multiple purposes, including routing, geocoding, and cartography, and is intended to be the single authoritative source of centerline information in Monroe County.

idPoC.rpOrgName: Monroe County Department of Environmental Services

rpCntInfo.cntInstr: Please contact Alex Nies for any questions related to this dataset.

resMaint.maintNote: Updates are made to the centerlines when new street information is provided to DES by the 9-1-1 Emergency Communications Department (ECD) and new subdividion maps are provided by Monroe County Real Property Services. Centerlines are digitized or modified from this information, as well as from the latest aerial photography, street abandonment and dedication reports, and input from municipalities.

dataIdInfo.idCredit: Development of the centerline file began in 1999 when the Genesee Transportation Council contracted with the Genesee/Finger Lakes Regional Planning Council (G/FLRPC) to create a road file with accurately positioned street centerlines and corresponding address ranges. With involvement from Monroe County, G/FLRPC rectified Enhanced TIGER/Line Files to Monroe County's digital real property tax parcels. Monroe County Department of Environmental Services (DES) obtained the rectified centerline file in 2001 and has enhanced and maintained it ever since (2001, Monroe County Department of Environmental Services, Rochester, NY).

dataLineage.statement:
Development of the centerline file began in 1999 when the Genesee Transportation Council contracted with the Genesee/Finger Lakes Regional Planning Council (G/FLRPC) through the Unified Planning Work Program to create a road file with accurately positioned street centerlines and corresponding address ranges. With involvement from Monroe County, G/FLRPC rectified Enhanced TIGER/Line Files to Monroe County's digital real property tax parcels. Monroe County GIS Services Division obtained the rectified street centerline file in 2001. Digital aerial photography was used to update the file, segments were added to represent town boundaries and railroads, and the centerlines were processed to remove unnecessary segments. New York State and Monroe County Department of Transportation data was used to assign interstate, state and county route numbers. Road class information was enhanced and roads were additionally classified by jurisdiction. Monroe County Department of Transportation requested that all road segments run from south-to-north and from west-to-east. Arc/Info AML routines were used to flip roads that were not running in the requested direction. Arc/Info AML routines were also used to assign route and section numbers to each road segment. A route number was assigned to each street based on the street name, and each segment within a route was assigned a segment number.
The street centerline file was used to develop an inventory of nodes or intersections. Each intersection was identified by the name of the roads, railroads or town boundaries that met at the intersection point. Intersections were categorized by type using aerial photography to place each intersection into one of over twenty classes, for example, cul-de-sac, dead end, railroad crossing, town line, at grade, at bridge, etc.
In May of 2008, several fields were added to the centerlines to make them suitable for routing. New York State Department of Transportation bridge data was used to help identify all bridge locations to assign F_ZLEV and T_ZLEV data. The New York State Office of Cyber Security & Critical Infrastructure Coordination (CSCIC) NYS Streets (ALIS data layer) dataset and data provided by the City of Rochester was used to assign one-way street restrictions. Information from the New York State Department of Transportation and the Towns of Brighton, Perinton, Pittsford, and Webster were used to assign speed limit attributes. Monroe County GIS Services Division staff estimated remaining speed limits and created hierarchy data based on road types and jurisdictions.
New street information is provided by the 9-1-1 Emergency Communications Department (ECD), and periodically, current tax parcels are obtained from the Monroe County Real Property Services and used to update the centerline file. The latest aerial photography, street abandonment and dedication reports, and municipal input are all utilized to keep the Monroe County centerline file accurate and current (2001, Monroe County Department of Environmental Services, Rochester, NY).
